  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Node dropping is a method of simulating data missing or nodes dropping, which improves the robustness of the model by randomly dropping a certain percentage of the nodes and their connections.",
    "The probability of node dropping usually follows a uniform distribution, and the a priori behind this is that dropped nodes do not significantly affect the overall semantic information of the graph.",
    "Attribute masking increases the model's sensitivity to local structural information by randomly masking the attributes of some nodes, which forces the model to utilize contextual information to predict these masked attributes, rather than relying too much on individual node information.",
    "Edge-level augmentation consists of edge perturbation and edge feature masking.",
    "Edge perturbation perturbs the connected structure of a graph by randomly adding or deleting edges to the graph, which simulates noise injection or edge deletion to enhance the robustness of the model to changes in the graph structure (Ding et al. 2022)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Edge perturbation perturbs the connected structure of a graph by randomly adding or deleting edges to the graph, which simulates noise injection or edge deletion to enhance the robustness of the model to changes in the graph structure (Ding et al. 2022)."
